Chicago has had Light Rail (above ground subway) since the late 1800's, and Louisville still does not sadly!!! 

HISTORY OF THE L
Beginning in the 1870s, as Chicago grew at an incredibly rapid pace, private companies laid rail tracks downtown and began introducing streetcars pulled by horses. In the 1880s, these horse-drawn trolleys were replaced by cable car services. But this form of transportation couldn‚Äôt handle a high volume of passengers and it added to street congestion.

On June 6, 1892, the first elevated‚Äîor ‚ÄúL‚Äù‚Äîtrain ran from 39th (now Pershing Road) and State streets to Congress Parkway and Wabash Avenue. By 1893, the Chicago and South Side Rapid Transit Railroad extended this line to Jackson Park, the site of the World‚Äôs Columbian Exposition of 1893. Today, this section of track is still part of the Green Line.

Multiple privately-operated train lines transported Chicagoans in the 1890s. However, these trains deposited people just outside the central business district‚Äîan area referred to as ‚Äúthe Loop‚Äù due to the cable cars that once created a loop around several blocks. A wealthy and controversial financier named Charles Tyson Yerkes soon changed all of this. Despite his sometimes illegal business practices, he had a lasting impact on Chicago by building elevated tracks above downtown streets to connect train lines together. Yerkes essentially created the Loop L we know today.

The first full circuit of the Loop was completed in 1897. Its steel structure was designed by bridge designer John Alexander Low Waddell. The iconic riveted steel-plate form resembles that of the Eiffel Tower (1889) and the original Ferris Wheel (1893).

All of Chicago‚Äôs trains were either elevated or at street grade until the 1940s. With funding from the Federal Works Agency‚Äîpart of President Franklin D. Roosevelt‚Äôs New Deal‚Äîthe State Street Subway, now part of the Red Line, opened in 1943. The Dearborn Street Subway, now part of the Blue Line, opened in 1951, following a construction delay during World War II. https://youtu.be/Sbq8uf25KWc?si=ssmwqb76ZzsmrSG5

The estimated cost to build the East End tunnels in Prospect, Kentucky was $338 million in 2014. The tunnels were part of the Kentucky approach to a new bridge. 
Explanation 
The tunnels were twin, two-lane tunnels that would carry traffic to and from the new bridge.
The tunnels were built under the Drumanard property, which is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
The tunnels were part of the Ohio River Bridges Project, which cost $242.34 million in total.

The Background Story

Plans for an East End bridge date back to at least 1969. Part of the problem with building it has long been that the Kentucky approach to this bridge would pass through the town Prospect, arguably the Louisville area‚Äôs most affluent and influential suburb. (For readers in Central Indiana, think ‚ÄúZionsville‚Äù or Southwest Clay Township in Carmel and you‚Äôll have the picture). The wealthy and influential residents there were long able to stymie progress on the East End bridge. They also had an ally in Louisville major Jerry Abramson, who greatly feared a beltway connection that would allow traffic to bypass downtown Louisville. He promoted a new downtown bridge instead.

In the grand tradition of political compromise, Indiana and Kentucky agreed to build both bridges. This was in part possible because of a city-county merger in Louisville, which reduced the fear of downtown lobby because they would still control revenues from any East End growth the bridge might spawn. Hence was born the fiction of ‚Äútwo bridges, one project‚Äù even though there is no real transportation necessity to link the two and either one has independent utility.

But the Prospect residents were never going to give up. As part of their plan to kill the East End bridge, they managed to get the Dumanard Estate put onto the National Register of Historic Places to make it much more difficult to route a roadway through it. After the original listing that included the home and gardens, the listing was later expanded to include the entire 55-acre grounds.

If you are wondering how building two bridges got to be $4.1 billion in the first place, this is an example of how. To avoid impacting this single historic property, Kentucky agreed to build a $261 million tunnel underneath the estate. (LEO Weekly discussed this in an article called ‚ÄúThe $260 Million Home.‚Äù)

The stunning thing about this tunnel is that the path of the road doesn‚Äôt actually affect any buildings, as this graphic from Broken Sidewalk illustrates:

If spending $260 million on this sounds ludicrous to you, then you are getting a sense of why Indiana shouldn‚Äôt be touching it with a ten foot pole.

A few readers were discussing Louisville‚Äôs old light rail proposal circa 2002 called Transportation Tomorrow (T2), so I decided to post the old renderings and route map in case anyone else needed a refresher.

From the project abstract at the U.S. DOT‚Äôs Context Sensitive Solutions site:

Travel and congestion in the South Central Corridor have dramatically increased due to population and employment growth within the Louisville Metropolitan Area (LMA). An important indicator of congestion has been growth in trips on I-65 that neither begin nor end in the LMA, but are ‚Äúthrough trips‚Äù on the interstate system. The combined travel on I-65 for local, regional and through trips has resulted in slower and less predictable travel times and reduced mobility for many interlocking travel markets in the South Central Corridor. Accessibility to jobs, business establishments, and cultural, entertainment, institutional and public service destinations is deteriorating and is considered a primary limiting factor to social and economic development. Neighborhoods are affected by the diversion of some longer trips to the local street system. Existing bus transit operates in mixed traffic and experiences the same congestion as a private automobile. In most circumstances, the rising congestion penalizes the transit traveler more so than the automobile traveler when both in-vehicle and out-of-vehicle travel times are taken into consideration. Existing transit, therefore, does not, and cannot, effectively compete with the single occupant vehicle (SOV).

Mock-up of light rail in Shelby Park. (Courtesy TARC)
Mock-up of light rail in Shelby Park. (Courtesy TARC)
But what has happened to the T2 light rail proposal since then? From TARC‚Äôs FAQ page: What happened to Light Rail?

The Light Rail project began with a Major Investment Study in 1996. After initial studies and analysis, rapid transit was prioritized over other alternatives and the locally preferred South Central Corridor was selected. The project entered into the Federal New Starts Program, and it was approved as a project in Horizon 2030, the region‚Äôs long-range transportation plan. The project then moved into Preliminary Engineering after the FTA issued a ‚Äòrecommended‚Äô rating and the draft environmental impact statement was completed. In 2004 ‚Äì 2006, the FTA implied that the movement into Final Design was not possible without a secured local match and the Draft Environmental Statement was not released for public review. At this point, TARC withdrew the Transportation Tomorrow project from New Starts program due to the inability to secure local funding.

In New York City, a congestion pricing toll covers the Central Business District in Manhattan. Passenger and small commercial vehicles pay $9 once per day that they enter the zone in peak hours (5 a.m. to 9 p.m. on weekdays and 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. on weekends) and $2.25 in non-peak times. Motorcycles pay less and certain bigger trucks and buses pay more. Taxis get a discounted rate per trip.

So, would something like that work in Atlanta?

In a press release, MTA shared that the new pricing system made for 219,000 less vehicles in that congestion zone in the first week, compared to that week a year prior, meaning traffic volume was down 7.5%.

MTA has not yet been able to correlate higher ridership on buses and trains with the new tolls. For one, tens of thousands of people already use the system, which is far more reliable and dense than MARTA in Atlanta.

Former Georgia Senator Vincent Fort has passed at the age of 68. Fort was a key political leader in Georgia for several decades. 

Fort, a member of the Democratic Party, came to the Atlanta area in the 1970s to attend Atlanta University (now Clark Atlanta University). He would remain a key fixture in Atlanta‚Äôs HBCU area by serving as a professor at Morehouse College and Morris Brown College. 

In the ‚Äô90s, Fort would delve into politics by being elected to the State Senate from the 39th District, representing City of Atlanta, East Point, College Park, Union City and unincorporated areas of Fulton County.

By 2011, Fort became the No. 2 person in the Senate Democratic caucus while also serving on Judiciary-Civil, Judiciary-Criminal, Education and Youth, Reapportionment and Redistricting, Interstate Cooperation, Urban Affairs, Marta Oversight and the Senate committees of Appropriations.

It was like you want to empty and there's no furniture, no art and nobody really wanted to come do anything here. So we worked at PBS to do community engagement work and asked the surrounding community like what would bring them here? What do they want to do here? A heartfelt thank you to Georgia's Own Credit Union and WSB-TV  for joining us at Hope Atlanta to assemble much-needed warming kits for our community!

In honor of their 90th anniversary, Georgia‚Äôs Own generously donated $6,000, enabling us to create 90 warming kits to help those experiencing homelessness stay safe and warm this winter. Remember to follow us @theurbanatlanta for all things development news!üëáüèΩ

A new 646 million dollar fleet of 56 modernized trains is set to debut in July 2025. Manufactured by Stadler Rail, the sleek CQ400 model features futuristic-looking four-car sets with open gangways for easier movement, and improved accessibility for bikes, strollers, and wheelchairs. 

MARTA also announced this week that it‚Äôs investing $500 million in a state-of-the-art train control system to improve safety, on-time performance, and efficiency. The new system will work seamlessly with the new trains, replacing the older 1970s cars. Testing is taking place in Salt Lake City, with the first trains scheduled for service in about half a year‚Äôs time. 

One cool aspect: the front of each vehicle will be lit with LED colors that correspond to each rail line.

Bravo Judge Rosie Speedlin Gonzalez bringing focus to domestic violence in San Antonio and recognized by the New York Times. 

One City‚Äôs Attempt to Change How Domestic Violence Is Tackled
San Antonio has long had a high rate of family violence. An unusual court is trying to intervene before the violence turns deadly.

By Edgar Sandoval
Reporting from San Antonio
New York Times
Dec. 3, 2024, 5:00 a.m. ET

On a sweltering July night, Jesse Falcon was so high on cocaine, marijuana and alcohol that he would later say that he barely remembered the explosion of violence that happened.

Convinced that his girlfriend was pursuing another man at a social gathering at their apartment complex in San Antonio, he began attacking the man. When his girlfriend tried to intervene, he shoved her so hard that she was left with a gash on her arm.

Mr. Falcon, 21, did recall one thing about the evening: ‚ÄúI was full of rage,‚Äù he said.

Cases like Mr. Falcon‚Äôs are troublingly familiar to court officials in San Antonio, which has long been plagued with a high rate of domestic violence. ‚ÄúThey leave jail angrier and more resentful, and the trauma continues,‚Äù said Rosie Speedlin Gonzalez, a family violence judge in the city.

A court run by Judge Gonzalez is trying a different approach: providing the abusers with a chance to change.

First-time offenders like Mr. Falcon can avoid becoming another statistic in the long string of men ‚Äî and a growing number of women ‚Äî who go to jail for hurting their families, if they are accepted into a family violence diversion program run by Judge Gonzalez‚Äôs court, which is known as Reflejo, Spanish for reflection.

The problem is hardly unique to San Antonio, a Latino-majority metropolis in South Texas. Much of the country saw a record spike in domestic violence cases during the coronavirus pandemic as lockdowns, job losses and alcohol consumption drove people into tense situations indoors.

Many cities have tried to address the problem, and rates in several cities are declining once again. San Antonio is among the places that have assigned more detectives to domestic violence cases. It is also conducting ‚Äúlethality assessments,‚Äù in which officers ask a series of questions to determine whether a victim is in danger of serious violence or even death if an intervention does not occur.

But the city felt an urgency to do even more. San Antonio has consistently ranked among the top 20 large cities for rates of aggravated domestic violence ‚Äî higher than Las Vegas, Philadelphia and Atlanta, according to a survey by the Council of Criminal Justice that was released in October. San Antonio also stood out for having a large share of underreported incidents, said Alex Piquero, a professor of criminology at the University of Miami who was one of the study‚Äôs lead authors.

The new court is one of a handful across the country that provide incentives as well as accountability for perpetrators, aimed at helping them control violent impulses before they become deadly.
In exchange for seeing their charges expunged, offenders who appear in Judge Gonzalez‚Äôs court are required to complete an intensive program of frequent court appearances, counseling, treatment for addiction and random drug and alcohol testing.

On a recent afternoon, Mr. Falcon and a group of men who had all been arrested at one point for assaulting a romantic partner or a household member gathered in the judge‚Äôs chambers. Mr. Falcon soon found himself answering uncomfortable questions. A monitor he was required to wear had detected alcohol in his system, a violation of the program‚Äôs rules that could send him back to jail.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôll go a long way if you re-examine your steps,‚Äù Judge Gonzalez said, shooting him a stern look. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre young. I want to see you do great things.‚Äù

This year, the nine family violence homicides in Bexar County, the unincorporated area around San Antonio, surpassed the number in each of the past three years, according to the county sheriff‚Äôs office. The city of San Antonio has also seen a troubling rise in domestic violence cases.

In 2019, the escalating number of cases prompted hundreds of people, many of them women, to descend on a town-hall meeting where they described chokings, beatings and other episodes of violence committed regularly, mostly by men in their families.

A judge ordered the creation of a commission on domestic violence to help address the problem.

Abusers tend to come from poor neighborhoods and often numb the memories of their own childhood traumas with substance abuse, said John Vacca, who runs a class known as Pathways to Healing, a requirement for those in Judge Gonzalez‚Äôs program.

Mr. Vacca, who served time in jail for gang-related offenses as a young man, today tries to help people recognize the triggers that lead them to violent outbursts. On a recent evening in a community center, Mr. Vacca welcomed several people who are part of the court‚Äôs program and made eye contact with Mr. Falcon, who sat in the front row, wearing a shy smile. Mr. Vacca wrote down two words on a chalkboard: Anger. Healing.

‚ÄúNobody teaches you about confusion ‚Äî it‚Äôs the beginning of anger, escalating to rage,‚Äù Mr. Vacca said as he paced in front of them. ‚ÄúOnce you feel that confusion coming up, that‚Äôs your warning signal.‚Äù
For Judge Gonzalez, who works closely with Mr. Vacca, the idea of a court like Reflejo seemed like common sense. Even before being elected as a judge in 2018, she said, she had grown frustrated while working as a lawyer and a social worker; there seemed to be a revolving door of people who were continually rearrested for assaulting a loved one.

‚ÄúMany reoffend, not knowing why,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúThey don‚Äôt understand where these emotions are coming from.‚Äù
When she started pitching the idea of a program for abusers, not victims, she was met with resistance. One politician told her, ‚ÄúNobody wants to help a violent offender ‚Äî it‚Äôs bad politics,‚Äù Judge Gonzalez recalled.

Legislation to create the court, written with the help of the judge‚Äôs wife, Stacy Speedlin Gonzalez, a scholar who has been open about her own struggles with abuse and domestic violence, was sponsored by two local lawmakers and signed into law by Gov. Greg Abbott, a Republican, in 2019. The court began in earnest a year later.

The court has since graduated 35 offenders, with only one of them being rearrested so far. Judge Gonzalez said she was aware of only two similar courts, one in Ohio and another in Florida.

It is hard to measure whether the program has worked where it matters most: inside families. Women who had a partner participating in the Reflejo court declined to be interviewed about it.

And not everyone agrees with its methods. Marta Pelaez, who runs Family Violence Prevention Services, an organization that runs a shelter and works to reduce family violence, said she found it hard to believe that an abuser could heal long-held, violent traits in a ‚Äúmatter of weeks.‚Äù Real change comes after years, if not a lifetime, of treatment, she said.

‚ÄúAnything that is close to 90 percent I‚Äôm very suspicious of,‚Äù Ms. Pelaez said, citing the court‚Äôs success rate. ‚ÄúIt is not possible to shift your attitude that dramatically. It would take years and years for a person to shift.‚Äù

Still, Mr. Falcon said he believed that without the Reflejo court, he would still be abusing drugs and making poor decisions. In the past year, he said, he has learned to regulate his emotions and follow rules. ‚ÄúAt the beginning it was hard to stay positive,‚Äù Mr. Falcon said. ‚ÄúBut I am glad I have stayed on track. I realized that they only want the best for us.‚Äù

He said the therapy had helped him think about the role his own family history played in his life. He was raised by a single mother who struggled to support the family with a job as a waitress. His father was in and out of prison. And he had faced relentless bullying at school, with classmates often making fun of his weight by mooing while he waited in line in the cafeteria, sometimes hitting him, he said.

Years later, he said, he found himself lashing out at the people he cared about, but had no idea how to seek help. ‚ÄúAs Hispanics, it is very difficult to talk about emotions,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt seek therapy. It was very stigmatized.‚Äù

The other men in the program shared similar stories. Shawn Sullivan, 37, said he was 10 when he was forced to clean the area where his grandfather had just shot his step-grandfather in the head.
James Nicholson, 30, recalled that his mother, who struggled with mental illness and alcoholism, slapped him so hard when he was 4 years old that he lost several teeth.
They had paid it painfully forward: Mr. Sullivan said he was arrested after getting into a physical fight with a former boyfriend. Mr. Nicholson was arrested after striking his wife in what had begun as a petty fight.

At times, some of the people in the program falter.
Deonte Hawkins, 23, a friend of Mr. Falcon‚Äôs who is also enrolled in the program, was taken into custody recently after missing some of his required substance abuse meetings.

For that hearing, Judge Gonzalez had called in Mr. Hawkins‚Äôs wife to sit next to him. She sobbed uncontrollably as the judge tried to reason with him.
‚ÄúGive us some insight because we are at a loss,‚Äù the judge told Mr. Hawkins. ‚ÄúWe want to help you. Is that what you want, to hurt her like that? You love her, right?‚Äù

Mr. Hawkins lowered his head. His wife dried her tears and watched as court officers handcuffed him and took him away. Judge Gonzalez later said that Mr. Hawkins was doing better and had gotten back on track.

Walking out of court that day, Mr. Falcon said he did not want to find himself in his friend‚Äôs shoes. He said he had found a good job working as a barista at a coffee shop, and, while he was not thinking about starting a family anytime soon, he was not ruling it out for later. First, he said, he would have to do a little more growing.

‚ÄúMy attitude toward life has changed,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI know how to respond to situations now. I‚Äôm a different person.‚Äù

Edgar Sandoval covers Texas for The Times, with a focus on the Latino community and the border with Mexico. He is based in San Antonio. More about Edgar Sandoval

MARTA will move forward with its plan to renovate the Five Points Station after reaching a compromise with the City of Atlanta over pedestrian and bus access.

Work to transform the transit system‚Äôs busiest station was slated to begin in July, but MARTA paused the project after Mayor Andre Dickens, city officials, and riders opposed plans to close the station and reroute buses.

Dickens also questioned the cost of the project following a city audit and expressed concerns over the station being closed during the World Cup 2026 matches set for nearby Mercedes-Benz Stadium.

Now, MARTA says one station entrance will remain open during construction, allowing for street-level and elevator access, as well as bus pick-up and drop-off.

#Atlanta has purchased the site of the former #Elleven45 Lounge as part of the #Atlanta #BeltLine‚Äôs expansion into #Buckhead, specifically focusing on affordable housing and commercial development. The #BeltLine has acquired nearly 90 acres of land, including 20 acres in 2023, to ensure long-term affordability and equitable development. 

One notable project is the affordable mixed-use development at 425 Garson Drive in Buckhead/Lindbergh, which will feature permanently affordable housing and commercial space near the Lindbergh MARTA station and along the future Northeast Trail.

GA Representative @votesaira knows more about voter protection in Georgia than *anyone*. She‚Äôs worked as the director of voter protection for the Democratic Party of Georgia and the Georgia director of voter protection for the Biden 2020 campaign. Here‚Äôs what she wants you to know:

- VOTE EARLY: Not only is early voting easier (more locations to vote and shorter lines), but it helps prevent chaos on Election Day itself. Many of the new regulations are designed to make voting take longer. On Election Day, expect long lines to vote.
- CHECK YOUR REGISTRATION: Over 100,000 voters have been removed from voter rolls. Check your status and register before tomorrow. 
- GET INVOLVED: Come to the State Election Board meeting on October 8th at 9:00am in room 341 at the Capitol in downtown Atlanta. Park in the Pete Hackney parking deck or take MARTA.
- LOCAL ELECTIONS MATTER: Local elections impact your daily life more than the presidency. Vote down the ballot.

Railcars once filled with bustling commuters in the city of Atlanta are now 65 feet below the Atlantic Ocean and filled with inquisitive fish, sea turtles and coral.

At the end of last year, the Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority dumped two railcars off Georgia‚Äôs coast as part of a program to develop reef habitats and marine wildlife with the Georgia Department of Natural Resources Reef Project. Any hazardous materials were removed first, and they were inspected by the US Coast Guard.

In August, the DNR Coastal Resources Division made its first dive to check on the cars and discovered soft coral beginning to grow and at least nine species of game fish.

Read more at the link in @cnn‚Äôs bio.

The Atlanta City Council has approved new ordinances that could significantly reshape the city's core by restricting where data centers can be developed. The legislation, which bars new data centers from being built near the BeltLine and within a half-mile of MARTA stations, is designed to prioritize human spaces over industrial use.

Atlanta's data center market has been one of the fastest-growing in the nation, driven by increased demand for digital infrastructure. However, city leaders are concerned that these developments could encroach on valuable urban space that is better used for public amenities.

The new restrictions will take effect once Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens signs them.

The State Transportation Board of Georgia approved the selection of a private sector partner for the Georgia 400 Express Lanes Project on Thursday. This allows the Public Private Partnership project to move forward, according to a release. 

In general, the project will add new express lanes in both directions along an approximately 16-mile section of Georgia 400 from the North Springs MARTA Station (Exit 5C) in Fulton County to approximately one mile north of McFarland Parkway (Exit 12) in Forsyth County. Like existing express lanes in the state, the new one will have variable-priced tolls that allow drivers to bypass congestion.

Chanell Crosby, 35, was found dead inside the back of a vehicle around 2 p.m. on July 19 in the area of the West End MARTA station, police said. The discovery of her body came a day after her family filed a missing persons report with Atlanta Police on July 18. Her family said she was last seen on July 14.

Her death came two years after both her 13-year-old son, Jamiren Crosby, and her brother were both shot and killed months apart in 2022.

An autopsy report for Chanell's death was released to 11Alive on Tuesday. Her cause of death was revealed to be a gunshot wound to the head, with her manner of death being ruled a homicide, according to the Fulton County Medical Examiner.

The NAHB Awards Program is now accepting applications and that including the Best in American Living Awards. Take a look at one of last year's winners, a gorgeous development for students in Atlanta, Georgia.

When you can‚Äôt build out, build up. This thoughtfully considered tower rises 25 stories to take full advantage of its half-acre footprint within walking distance to Georgia Tech‚Äôs campus in the heart of Tech Square, Midtown Atlanta‚Äôs hub for startups and research centers.

Whistler offers 565 beds in 168 units and features more than 17,300 square feet of boutique-style amenities. Students can treat themselves to craft coffee and artisan pastries at the on-site Daydreamer cafe, exercise in the expansive fitness center with yoga and spin studios, or lounge poolside on the rooftop deck while enjoying panoramic skyline views.

The 284,839-square-foot property is served with one level of basement parking totaling 25 spaces to encourage a continued reliance on biking, walking, scooters and public transportation with proximity to Atlanta‚Äôs MARTA lines. The dynamic design of mid-gray tones starts with a stacked base of amenities to activate the street, and draws the eye up with slender, mini towers and rhythmically shifting balconies slightly offset from each other to create a dynamic facade instead of a static block.

Whistler accomplishes the city‚Äôs initiative to create a more pedestrian-friendly environment, while providing students unmatched amenity spaces and views of the city and campus.

post_body_text: Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens has asked MARTA to consider a 10-year fix to the canopy at Five Points station, rather than proceeding with a permanent fix as planned, the transit agency says.
Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens has asked MARTA to consider a 10-year fix to the canopy at Five Points station, rather than proceeding with a permanent fix as planned, the transit agency says.
Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens has asked MARTA to consider a 10-year fix to the canopy at Five Points station, rather than ... https://t.co/6xzToEHVkM

The board of directors for the Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority (MARTA) will meet Thursday for the first time since the agency postponed its massive renovation project at the Five Points station in downtown Atlanta.

post_body_text: Georgia: A MARTA police officer has been rushed to the hospital after a crash in southwest Atlanta early Tuesday morning.According to MARTA officials, the officer was responding to back up another officer at the Garnet Station with lights and sirens activated as they crossed through the intersection of Lee and West Whitehall streets and collided with another vehicle, causing both vehicles to leave the road and come to rest alongside the Norfolk Railroad tracks.Both the officer and the driver of the other vehicle were transported to a hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. post_body_text: MARTA officials announced last week that they are postponing the closure of street access to Five Points station during its renovation. The announcement comes after pushback from Atlanta‚Äôs elected officials.

MARTA officials announced last week that they are postponing the closure of street access to Five Points station during its renovation. The announcement comes after pushback from Atlanta‚Äôs elected officials.

MARTA officials announced Wednesday that they are postponing the closure of street access to Five Points station during its renovation. The announcement comes after pushback from Atlanta‚Äôs elected officials.

MARTA officials announced Wednesday that they are postponing the closure of street access to Five Points station during its renovation. The announcement comes after pushback from Atlanta‚Äôs elected officials.

Service impacts related to Phase 1 of MARTA's Five Points Station Transformation project have been halted, the transit authority announced Wednesday. 

MARTA had previously announced a schedule for implementing customer impacts starting this Saturday, but those plans have now been put on hold. 

Eight downtown bus routes scheduled to relocate on July 6 will now remain stationed out of Five Points, and street-level access to the station set to close on July 29 will remain open. 

This comes after transit advocates and Mayor Andre Dickens voiced concerns about plans to close street access during the project.

Click the link in the bio for the full story. 

#11Alive #Atlanta #Marta #FivePoints

Service impacts related to Phase 1 of MARTA's Five Points Station Transformation project have been halted, the transit authority announced Wednesday. 

MARTA had previously announced a schedule for implementing customer impacts starting this Saturday, but those plans have now been put on hold. 

Eight downtown bus routes scheduled to relocate on July 6 will now remain stationed out of Five Points, and street-level access to the station set to close on July 29 will remain open. 

This comes after transit advocates and Mayor Andre Dickens voiced concerns about plans to close street access during the project.

Click the link in the bio for the full story. 

#11Alive #Atlanta #Marta #FivePoints

Service impacts related to Phase 1 of MARTA's Five Points Station Transformation project have been halted, the transit authority announced Wednesday. 

MARTA had previously announced a schedule for implementing customer impacts starting this Saturday, but those plans have now been put on hold. 

Eight downtown bus routes scheduled to relocate on July 6 will now remain stationed out of Five Points, and street-level access to the station set to close on July 29 will remain open. 

This comes after transit advocates and Mayor Andre Dickens voiced concerns about plans to close street access during the project.

Click the link in the bio for the full story. 

#11Alive #Atlanta #Marta #FivePoints

The project would affect bus routes and street access at their busiest station for 18 months, according to MARTA.

Atlanta found out that Five Points Station would be closed to pedestrian entry for four years (starting next month) only a couple of weeks ago, at a Council committee meeting. 

No one outside of MARTA staff appears to have known beforehand. It was a surprise, which stinks. 

1/2

Atlanta's Five Points MARTA station could soon have limited access to complete a four-year renovation project, despite protection and even a request from the mayor.

According to the transit system, travelers will be closed to the hub coming off the street beginning July 29. While trains will continue to run through the station, allowing passengers to transfer, there will be limited access to elevators. 

This would hinder riders with disabilities, who would then need to use MARTA Mobility shuttles to change direction, adding to their commute.

The MARTA station at Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport reopened its turnstiles to passengers on Monday after a six-week hiatus ‚Äî just in time for the Memorial Day travel rush.
https://t.co/faBo1VygKQ

After six weeks of closures for renovation, MARTA's Airport Station is reopening on Monday, signaling a sigh of relief for Atlanta commuters.

The renovation project began on April 8 and included work on the concourse and platform levels, including installing new flooring, lighting, and infrastructure for a new elevator.

MARTA officials said shutting down that area helped reduce construction time by 17 months.

So it makes it even better as trains once again transport passengers to their travels or work they're met on the platform by a fresh new look following six weeks of hard work and renovations. A lot of people are saying, wow and immediately start to do the look around, which is kind of, which is great to be as a construction person because now they're looking around and noticing all the work that's being done between new lighting and amenities. Jermaine White, senior project manager for Marta, hopes the new aesthetics offer a better experience. Just the whole feel and look at the station is what I'm most proud of. If you look upstairs, the moment you get off the train, it's a brighter feel. The texture of the services is much better. Uh The color wise, everything is just there. Passengers taking time as they pass through to share appreciation before heading to their next stop. It's amazing. I mean, I can't say it enough. I mean, I'm gonna be excited to come great experience as always, but it's always good to have nice and shiny things, nice and shiny things. You got to love a little love for Marta, especially coming out of this anticipated renovation. And Mar a very strategically chose this time period this low between spring break and Memorial Day weekend to get this work done. Now, even though the station has reopened, the trains are running once again, the work behind the scenes continues with the full renovation expected to be complete more like 2026 in the spring. In the meantime, Marta is very much ready for the influx of passengers expected here at Hartsfield Jackson as we head into the holiday weekend, live at Hartsfield Jackson International Airport. I'm Lisa Lucas. Send it back to you.

Consistent with MARTA‚Äôs ongoing commitment to fiscal responsibility, the Authority is hosting public hearings for consideration of the proposed fiscal year 2025 Operating and Capital Budgets. 

You are invited to attend these public hearings in May.

Public Hearing Details: 

IN PERSON
 
WHAT:‚Äã Proposed FY 2025 Operating and Capital Budgets public hearing
WHEN:‚Äã Wednesday, May 15th at 7 p.m. (Community Exchange ‚Äì 6 p.m.) 
WHERE:‚Äã DeKalb Maloof Auditorium, 1500 Commerce Drive, Decatur, GA 30030

IN PERSON & VIRTUAL

WHERE:‚Äã MARTA Headquarters, 2424 Piedmont Road, Atlanta, GA 30324

Visit: www.itsmarta.com to join virtually (May 16th only)‚Äã
 
The MARTA Board will consider comments received during the hearings, as well as comments made via email and voicemail prior to final approval of the proposed FY 25 budget. Comments may be submitted no later than May 20, 2024, via voice message at 404-848-5299, sent to MARTA‚Äôs Office of External Affairs, 2424 Piedmont Road, N.E. Atlanta, GA 30324-3330, or emailed to publichearinginfo@itsmarta.com. 
#Claytonconnected

Police are investigating after a man was shot and killed inside of a MARTA train car in Atlanta on Thursday afternoon.

MARTA Police said they responded to the GWCC/CNN Center Station around 5:45 p.m. for a call of a person shot on the eastbound Blue Line train. The train was heading from H.E. Holmes. 

When officers got there, they tried to render first aid to the victim but he ultimately died. Police said they are still searching for the suspect.

Click the link in the bio for the full story. 

#11Alive #Marta #Atlanta #Shooting #Crime
GoogleAudioText: It was around 545 Thursday afternoon. Major Eugene Roberts says a 911 call came into Marta police. Dispatting us to the Omni-Dome for a person shot on the train. The blue line train heading eastbound from H.E. Holmes. In between H.E. Holmes and Omni-Dome incident happened. By the time officers got on scene witnesses were long gone, along with the shooter. It's unclear if cameras on the train caught the deadly shooting as for a motive. We don't know why it happened or the reasoning behind it. As far as security on Marta. We do have train patrol on our trains, officers on the trains.

We're getting a behind-the-scenes look at work to overhaul the Airport MARTA station.
GoogleAudioText: Live. Look now at Hartsfield Jackson International Airport a pretty day to fly today. We are getting a behind the scenes, look at work to overhaul the airport. Marta station, the station has been closed for three weeks now impacting 11,000 travelers a day. All right, so 11 lives, Jerry Carnes takes us inside and has an update on the progress being made while it is a disruption. Marta passengers are getting used to taking vans and buses to the airport instead of training one day. Some of those passengers like Kenya Taylor and her crew prefer a ride in a roomy charter bus much quicker than I thought it was because originally I believe they said like 12 minutes between shuttles, it was fast, it was comfortable, it was clean and quiet. It is not quiet behind these doors in an area temporarily off limits to the public where work is in full swing to give the airport Marta station a major facelift. The rails that typically carry trains are covered by scaffolding. Crews are removing and replacing the tile where passengers typically walk it have that nice shiny coat to it that there's been significant progress in the downstairs area around the turnstiles upstairs on the train platform, work is a little slower. The tiles are a little bit heavier, larger tiles. Project manager Jermaine White says work is ahead of schedule. Despite that Marta will stick to their plan to keep the airport station closed for six weeks. Instead of opening early, we'll extend the amount of work that we can do to get things done, we can do within that six week window. We'll do that. There will still be major work to do before the end of next year to complete the facelift. Most of it will take place while the trains are running for now. While scaffolding sits on the tracks, there are vans and buses instead of trains, the cleanliness and comfortable chair, so very nice. And there are people like Kenya Taylor who don't mind one bit.

ICYMI: At the April 17 Fulton County Board of Commissioners meeting,

 üéØBoard Members unanimously approved to restore Animal Control Services to the City of Atlanta.

 üéØMARTA representatives provided several capital improvement updates including the transformation of the Five Points Station and the rehab of the Airport and College Park Stations.

 üéØThe Board approved Cathy Woolard, former Chair of the Fulton County Board of Registration and Elections to once again serve in the role.

 üìÖThe next Board of Commissioners Meeting is scheduled for Wednesday, May 1.
GoogleAudioText: Hello, I'm Regina Waller, Communications Division Manager in External Affairs with your Board of Commissioners meeting, wrap up for the April 17, 2024 meeting. Board members unanimously approved to restore animal control services to the City of Atlanta. The vote comes after receiving a signed intergovernmental agreement for animal control services. Following a second quarter report, Marta Rep. Provided Board members with several capital improvement updates, including the transformation of the five-point station and the rehab of the Airport and College Park stations. In a majority vote, the Board approved Kathy Woolard, former chair of the Fulton County Board of Registration and Elections to once again serve in that role. The Board will serve as the interim chair following the recent resignation of current chair Patrice Perkins Hooker. Board members voted unanimously to approve a $100,000 contract between community development and with destination tomorrow, a nonprofit agency that will provide HIV testing and other services. The next Board of Commissioners meeting will be held for Wednesday, May 1.

Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens issued an administrative order on Thursday that identifies the locations for infill MARTA stations. 

This comes after the mayor previously announced that the city would partner with MARTA to build a new heavy rail station at the Murphy Crossing redevelopment project in addition to three infill stations. There will also be a corridor for a Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) line to connect the redeveloped Bowen Homes community with Ponce City Market. 

According to the order, the locations will be: Krog Street/Hulsey Yard, Joseph E. Boone, Murphy Crossing and Armour Yards.

Click the link in the bio for the full story.

Mayor Andre Dickens announced during his state of the city address, the new Marta infill stations will be at Krog Street, Joseph E Boone and Armor Yards. The newly signed administrative order also identifies a bus rapid transit route that will run from the redeveloped Bowen Holmes community to Ponce City market. GoogleAudioText: About 100 maintenance workers at the Atlanta airport say they will walk off the job if their concerns are not addressed. They made these demands Wednesday. During the Atlanta City Council Transportation Committee meeting, they mentioned allegations of sexual harassment with one employee saying that they were accosted by a supervisor and those of others with similar experiences. An hr representative encouraged those victims to report the behavior. Workers also say they are concerned about pay. They want a return of $4 an hour that was taken away a couple of years ago, the airport did release statements in response saying that they do take these allegations seriously and will look into each and every concern as far as the pay. They say that a compensation study is currently underway.

Let's take the time out to wish civil rights activist and Pastor Andrew Young a happy birthday today! Andrew Jackson Young (born 03/12/1932) was born in New Orleans, Louisiana, to Daisy Fuller Young, a school teacher, and Andrew Jackson Young, Sr., a dentist. Young's father hired a professional boxer to teach Andrew and his brother how to fight, so they could defend themselves. Young graduated from Howard University and earned a divinity degree from Hartford Seminary in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1955. Young was appointed to serve as pastor of a church in Marion, Alabama. It was there in Marion that he met Jean Childs, who later became his wife. Young became interested in Gandhi's concept of non-violent resistance as a tactic for social change. He encouraged African-Americans to register to vote in Alabama, and sometimes faced death threats while doing so. It was at this time that he became a friend and ally of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. In 1957, Young and Jean moved to New York City to accept a job with the Youth Division of the National Council of Churches. While in New York, Young regularly appeared on Look Up and Live, a weekly Sunday morning television program on CBS, produced by the National Council of Churches in an effort to reach out to secular youth. Young moved to Atlanta, Georgia, in 1961, and again worked on drives to register black voters. In 1960, he joined the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. Young was jailed for his participation in civil rights demonstrations, both in Selma, Alabama, and in St. Augustine, Florida. Young played a key role in the events in Birmingham, Alabama, serving as a mediator between the white and black communities. In 1964, Young was named executive director of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC), becoming, in that capacity, one of King's principal lieutenants. As a colleague and friend of Martin Luther King Jr., he was a strategist and negotiator during the Civil Rights Campaigns in Birmingham (1963), St. Augustine (1964), Selma (1965), and Atlanta (1966) that resulted in the passage of the Civil Rights Act and Voting Rights Act. He was with King in Memphis, Tennessee, when King was assassinated in 1968. In 1970, Andrew Young ran as a Democrat for Congress from Georgia, but was unsuccessful. After his defeat, Rev. Fred C. Bennette, Jr., introduced him to Murray M. Silver, an Atlanta attorney, who served as his campaign finance chairman. Young ran again in 1972 and won. He later was re-elected in 1974 and in 1976. During his four-plus years in Congress, he was a member of the Congressional Black Caucus, and was involved in several debates regarding foreign relations, including the decision to stop supporting the Portuguese attempts to hold on to their colonies in southern Africa. Young also sat on the powerful Rules Committee and the Banking and Urban Development Committee. Young opposed the Vietnam War, [4] helped enact legislation that established the U.S. Institute for Peace, established the Chattahoochee River National Park and negotiated federal funds for MARTA and the Atlanta Highways. In 1977, President Jimmy Carter appointed Young to serve as the United States Ambassador to the United Nations. Young resigned from Congress, and his seat was taken by Wyche Fowler after a special election. Although the US and the UN enacted an arms embargo against South Africa, as President Carter‚Äôs UN ambassador, Andrew Young vetoed economic sanctions. Young caused controversy when, during a July 1978 interview with French newspaper Le Matin de Paris, while discussing the Soviet Union and its treatment of political dissidents, he said, "We still have hundreds of people that I would categorize as political prisoners in our prisons," in reference to jailed civil-rights and anti-war protestors. In response, U.S. Representative Larry McDonald (D-GA) sponsored a resolution to impeach Young, but the measure failed 293 to 82. Carter referred to it in a press conference as an "unfortunate statement". In 1979, Young played a leading role in advancing a settlement in Rhodesia with Robert Mugabe and Joshua Nkomo, who had been two of the military leaders in the Rhodesian Bush War, which had ended in 1979. The settlement paved the way for Mugabe to take power as Prime Minister of the newly-formed Republic of Zimbabwe. There had been a general election in 1979, bringing Bishop Abel Muzorewa to power as leader of the United African National Council leading to the short-lived country of Zimbabwe Rhodesia. Young refused to accept the election's results, and described the election as "neofascist", a sentiment echoed by United Nations Security Council Resolution 445 and 448. The situation was resolved the next year with the Lancaster House Agreement and the establishment of Zimbabwe. Young's favoring of Mugabe and Nkomo over Muzorewa and his predecessor and ally, Ian Smith, was, and remains, controversial. Many African-American activists, including Jesse (truncated)

NEWS: Sen. Ossoff, Senator Reverend Raphael Warnock, and Congresswoman Nikema Williams today announced new Federal grants to upgrade transportation & recreation infrastructure for Georgia families ‚Äî including historic grants to fund phase 1 of The Stitch & a new multi-use trail connecting the AtlantaBeltLine with the Flint River Trail. A $157 million Federal investment will fund Phase 1 of The Stitch project, which aims to reconnect downtown Atlanta by capping the I-75/I-85 interstate with a new 4-acre park and multimodal improvements across the street network with better connectivity to MARTA‚Äôs Civic Center. A $50 million Federal investment in the Southside Trail will help advance the Atlanta Regional Commission's project to build a new multi-use trail ‚Äî which would help connect schools, hospitals, job centers, and MARTA rail between the BeltLine and the Flint River Trail. Sens. Ossoff and Rev. Warnock also announced additional grants for continued planning of projects to upgrade infrastructure across Georgia. The City of Savannah will receive a $1.8 million Federal investment for Savannah's I-16 flyover project, which aims to remove the flyover exit ramp over Martin Luther King, Jr. Boulevard to Montgomery Street & the associated adjacent ramps to improve connectivity. Athens-Clarke County will receive an $800,000 Federal grant to continue planning infrastructure upgrades along Hawthorne and Oglethorpe Avenues in downtown Athens, improving connectivity and increasing community safety. Macon-Bibb County will receive a $500,000 Federal grant for continued planning of upgrades to the Pleasant Hill Neighborhood, with plans to reconnect the community with Macon-Bibb County‚Äôs downtown business district.

post_body_text: Starting in April, travelers using MARTA to get to the Atlanta airport will need to give themselves a bit more time to arrive.
Atlanta airport MARTA station temporarily closing for renovations https://t.co/QuwCYwJs5Y
Although some construction has already started, most of the renovations will take place starting on April 8. The station will reopen on May 19.

The station will be closed from April 8 to May 19.

MARTA will close its Airport Station for six weeks from Monday, April 8 through Sunday, May 19 to renovate the concourse and platform levels. Day 13 of the AJC‚Äôs Black History Month series: One day in the 1960s, Dorothy Bolden stopped Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. while waiting on a bus. Two MARTA rail cars that once transported millions of Atlanta passengers around the city sank to the bottom of the sea floor near Savannah just before Christmas, joining existing artificial reefs like MC16 battle tanks and New York City subway cars. The rail reefs join 32 artificial reefs along the Georgia coastline that began in 1970 to create fish habitat. A decade ago, New York City donated its old fleet of subway cars, and again several years later, to the effort and now, Georgia‚Äôs public transportation system is piloting its fleet as part of a new disposition strategy.

THAT'S A JOB DOOMS HAS TAKEN SERIOUSLY SINCE 1972 AND HE SAYS PEOPLE TRUST THEM WITH THEIR LIVES TO REACH THEIR DESTINATION. HE CAN STILL REMEMBER THE FIRST DAY BEHIND THE WHEEL, GRADUATED ON A FRIDAY. IT WAS 18 CADETS IN MY CLASS. I WAS THE YOUNGEST ONE IS CALLED ME THE BABY BOY, SO I HAD AN UNCLE THAT HAD BEEN THERE 5.5 YEARS BEFORE. I STARTED THE BUSSES HUNDREDS 205 100. THOSE ARE THE BUSSES FROM 1953 50 BY AND THE IT WAS THE UNIT THAT WAS SIMILAR TO THE ONE THAT MS PARK REFUSED TO STAND UP IN. MARTA SURPRISED HIM WITH THIS SPECIAL BUS WITH HIS IMAGE, AND IT'S CURRENTLY IN SERVICE ON SEVERAL ROUTES PICTURE AND SHOCKED. THAT IS THE MOST AMAZING HONOR THAT YOU ESPECIALLY AS OPERATOR THAT YOU CAN RECEIVE PROCLAMATIONS FROM CITY COUNCIL, MAYORS AND COUNTY IS HONORING HIS WORK, BUT IT'S DO MESS WHO CONTINUES TO INSPIRE AND MOTIVATE OTHERS OPERATES THAT RELIEVE ME SEVERAL YEARS AGO, HE SAT AROUND ME. HE WAS ABOUT 1011 YEARS OLD BECAUSE HIS GRANDMOTHER USED TO WRAP ME ON THAT 98. AND UH, I INSPIRED HIM TO BE OPERATING. HE'S OPERATOR NOW AND HAS BEEN FOR SOME 2025 YEARS WITH OVER 2 MILLION MILES DRIVEN AND WITHOUT AN ACCIDENT AND NEARLY 3 MILLION PASSENGERS ARRIVING SAFELY WITH DO MISSED BEHIND THE WHEEL. HE SAYS HIS SOUL CONTINUES TO RUN ON GRATITUDE BY GOD'S GRACE. BY GOD'S GRACE. >>REPORTER: ALL RIGHT, AND BACK OUT HERE ALIVE. HE ALSO SAYS A MAJOR PART OF WHAT KEPT HIM GOING FOR SO LONG WAS HIS WIFE'S TEST FOR DECADES GOT UP WITH HIM AT 330 COOKED BREAKFAST AND REALLY SUPPORTED HIM. OF COURSE WE SALUTE HIM THIS EVENING

Mr. Coy Dumas, Jr. is a native of the Adamsville community of Atlanta, Georgia and in 1972, joined what was then called Atlanta Transit as a bus operator. He has run routes solely in West Atlanta over the past 50 years, and currently operates Route 853 out of the West Lake Station on the Blue Line.
Mr. Dumas has carried approximately 2.8 million passengers on his bus since he began his career in transit. He boasts a spotless driving record over his career and has never had a traffic accident, having driven over two million miles across the City of Atlanta. Now after 51 years of dedicated service to the citizens of Atlanta and Fulton County, he has decided to retire, but continue training new drivers as a consultant.

The Fulton County Board of Commissioners recognizes Coy Dumas, Jr. for his outstanding example of service, dedication, and professionalism with MARTA, and celebrates his retirement after 51 years of service, and does hereby proclaim Wednesday, November 15, 2023 as Coy Dumas Jr. Appreciation Day in Fulton County, Georgia.

Last week, Sen. Ossoff joined Soccer in the Streets, MARTA, Atlanta United FC, and local leaders to celebrate the new StationSoccer field in East Lake. Sen. Ossoff brought Republicans & Democrats together to deliver $1 million to Soccer in the Streets to build new fields across Metro Atlanta.

Last week, Sen. Ossoff joined Soccer in the Streets, MARTA, Atlanta United FC, and local leaders to celebrate the new StationSoccer field in East Lake. Sen. Ossoff brought Republicans & Democrats together to deliver $1 million to Soccer in the Streets to build new fields across Metro Atlanta. "We've created a place where kids can play safely, and what is more important than that?" Sen. Ossoff said. "What is more important than putting our minds together and pooling our resources to create sanctuaries for children to play with each other, to learn, and to pursue health & wellness?"

A man who'd been wanted in Atlanta for murder for nearly 28 years was finally caught this week during a routine traffic stop, according to the FBI.

The agency said in a release that Muhammed Bilal El-Amin was captured by the Oconee County Sheriff's Office, near Athens, in the course of the traffic stop.

He'd had a FBI reward out for his arrest since the early 2000s, after allegedly shooting a man in the face with a handgun at the Oakland City MARTA station in Atlanta in November 1994.

Read more: https://www.11alive.com/article/news/crime/muhammed-bilal-el-amin-wanted-1994-atlanta-murder-captured/85-54c2607a-8edf-43f1-bf69-9b5a386127ef

Join us on Tuesday, 9/19 from 2-6 pm at College Park, H.E. Holmes, Lindbergh Center, Doraville, Five Points, Kensington, and North Springs stations to celebrate #NationalVoterRegistrationDay!

Get informed about voting, renew your registration, or register for the first time. Don't miss out on the festivities at Five Points station with live music and more!

This year's participating non-profit partners are:

GA Coalition for the People's Agenda
Georgia STAND-UP
National Coalition of 100 Black Women, Metro Atlanta Chapter
New Georgia Project
Fulton County Government Voter Reg & Elections
It's In DeKalb Voter Reg & Elections
NAACP DeKalb County Branch - GA
Latino Community Fund -LCF Georgia
Naacp Clayton County Branch
Clayton County Alphas
Senior Coalition Caucus
Alpha Phi Alpha - Pi Gamma Lambda Chapter

For more information visit: https://itsmarta.com/marta-hosts-voter-registration-event.aspx

GoogleAudioText: Alright, let's talk about this Minecraft. It's a very popular game among the youngins and school. It could be a dream combination for some kids. It can be, and starting today, students at Atlanta Public Schools will be able to use the video game to envision a better future for their city. APS joined Mayor Andre Dickens to launch the Level Up Atlanta Minecraft Student Bill Challenge, and students had to answer just one question. How can we envision a connected, equitable and sustainable future that moves Atlanta forward but leaves no one behind? So Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens got some help from 5th grader John Howard, and this level up challenge allows students like Howard to reimagine 4 different Atlanta landmarks using an education based version of that popular game, Minecraft. The goal here is to teach students critical thinking. The Minecraft Challenge is is stimulating young minds and trying to get them creative, open minded, trying to be risk takers. Like they said, there's no bad ideas, there's just mistakes that kids need to work on. OK, so it all starts today at APS and students can submit their proposals. The district and city will feature the finalist coming up in January. All right, so.

post_body_text: It‚Äôs the first time the Atlanta BeltLine trail will connect to a MARTA transit station.
Atlanta's BeltLine is receiving the largest federal grant in its history, which will help connect a MARTA station to the BeltLine for the first time.
GoogleAudioText: Right now, the countdown continues in just six days. Runners will be lining up for a 4th of July tradition, the 2023 A JC Peachtree Rd. race. Tuesday, thousands will be battling their way through 6.2 miles down Peachtree Rd. Peachtree is always a fight to the finish, and as Caitlin Ross shows us, for one duo hoping to cross the finish line this year, that struggle is worth every step. Traffic violation. Officer Melinda Lim isn't going to write Willie Hatchett a ticket. Make sure you get that. But their story spells out inspiration. She cares about the people, the relationship in the community. Willie met Officer Lim on the A JC Peachtree Rd. Race course last year, but he never saw her. And I heard so many great things about her, how she cared for me. He was just a mile into the race when he went down. I collapsed. Collapse mile into the race, Willie suffered cardiac arrest and Officer Lim was the first to respond. Everything was moving, everybody was running, and all of a sudden I see Willie just stop and he just collapsed. Doctors and nurses on the course rushed in to help. We just kept taking turns doing CPR because it was so high. It was so strenuous. After they got Willie into the ambulance, Officer Lim didn't see him again for months. I was worried about Willie. I I needed to know if he was OK. It was very concerning to me because he was down for so long. When Willie got out of the hospital, the two built a friendship step by step. Willie is a great father. He's a great friend. He's a great husband. I have heard nothing but great things about him. Those small steps adding up to a big idea. Officer Liam. Told me if you want to do it. I would do it with you. They plan to walk Peachtree together next week. Their friendship will endure long past the finish line. There'll be sometimes when I'm having a hard day at work and I forget why I do what I do, and then I remember. I remember Willie. I remember you like you're one of the reasons why I do what I do. Reporting in Atlanta, Caitlin Ross, 11 Live News and thank goodness she was there. Saved willies life. Truly amazing that they'll be walking it together. And remember, it is OK to walk if you get overheated. If you don't feel OK, take a moment, take a breath and walk. Make sure you hydrate that day too. And don't forget you can hang out with us to watch the race and all of the fun that comes with it. The bands, the Donuts, Some people even drink some beer as they're running. Don't worry, I won't tell. Our special coverage begins Tuesday, the 4th of July. Starting right here at 4:30 AM. I'll see you out there on the course happening now.

BIG NEWS: Sen. Ossoff, Senator Reverend Raphael Warnock, and Congresswoman Nikema Williams are delivering $25 million through the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law to accelerate construction of the Atlanta BeltLine Northeast Trail. The funds will be used for the construction of a 2.2-mile network of multi-use trails in northeast Atlanta between the Armour/Ottley and Lindbergh areas and connect the Atlanta BeltLine trail to MARTA's station at Lindbergh Center. The new funding will also add necessary safety upgrades to the development, including new and improved bridge structures, ADA-accessible ramps, crosswalks and signals, lights and security cameras, stormwater infrastructure, and landscaping.

Chelsea this is recycling at its finest it really is because right now Sean when Marta retires their old cars they're salvaged and stripped for parts in other states but this new program will send those cars below Seas to help create an artificial Reef we're looking to Reef two cars this summer from the Streets of Atlanta to the shores of Savannah some of Marta's oldest rail cars are heading to Georgia's Coast rail cars have been proven to be fully functional as artificial habitats offering support to smaller marine life Marta's sustainability director Richard Thomas says the cars will create a stable area for corals and algae to grow and will attract fish in other underwater organisms last week Marta's board of directors approved a multi-million dollar deal for a contracting company to clean and strip eight rail cars before they're submerged into the Atlantic Ocean by Georgia's Department of Natural Resources they could have material in them that needs specialty special care and cleaning and getting all of the solvents and grease and everything off so there's an environmental aspect to that according to the U.S department of the Interior the artificial Reef program began decades ago and has helped fuel not only under water environments but also local economies by increasing tourism and Commercial Fishing according to Georgia's Coastal Resources Division there are currently 30 artificial reefs along Georgia's Coast made of things like tugboats chicken cages and old barges Marta plans to Reef their first ever cars in August to avoid contact with an endangered species per federal guidelines the right whale mates off of Georgia and apparently during mating season they don't want them running into train cars that weren't there thank you and Marta leaders say that DNR is helping pay some of the bill though they did not clarify how much they are hoping to send two cars to the coast by the end of this summer reporting live in Atlanta Chelsea by 4 GoogleAudioText: This is your first look at the new Marta bus stops coming to the city starting this week. Now we all know the classic Marta bus stops. They've been around for years, they have more colors than information. These new stops are going to have route numbers and they're also going to have the terminating location for each route. So you'll know exactly where you're trying to go. And it will also have a QR code linking to Marta's website so you can get service alerts and better plan your trip. Each stop will have a six digit bus stop ID to help better identify the bus stop. Now according to Marta is going to take months for this to roll out completely, but they're starting this week on one of the busiest routes in the city, the number 39. Let me know what you think about the new bus stops in the comments.

post_body_text: MARTA issued a statement Tuesday afternoon, calling the city council's position "disappointing and disingenuous."

Atlanta City Council members held a press conference Tuesday to discuss an approved resolution by the council calling for a financial audit of the More MARTA Program. MARTA issued a statement Tuesday afternoon, calling the city council's position "disappointing and disingenuous."

HAPPY BIRTHDAY MR. ANDREW YOUNG JR. (ŒëŒ¶Œë)! Today, March 12th, we celebrate the 91st birthday of Andrew Jackson Young Jr. (March 12, 1932 in New Orleans, Louisiana); an African-American politician, diplomat, and activist. Beginning his career as a pastor, Young was an early leader in the civil rights movement, serving as executive director of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC) and a close confidant to Martin Luther King Jr. Young later became active in politics, serving as a U.S. Congressman from Georgia, United States Ambassador to the United Nations in the Carter Administration, and 55th Mayor of Atlanta. Since leaving office, Young has founded or served in many organizations working on issues of public policy and political lobbying. Andrew Young was born to Daisy Young, a schoolteacher, and Andrew Jackson Young, a dentist. Young's father hired a professional boxer to teach Andrew and his brother to defend themselves. In a 1964 interview with author Robert Penn Warren for his book, Who Speaks for the Negro?, Young recalls the tensions of segregation in New Orleans, especially growing up in a fairly well-to-do household. He recalls his parents trying to "compensate for segregation" by providing for their children but were reluctant to help less wealthy black communities in the area. Young, attended Dillard University for one year before graduating from Howard University. He then earned a divinity degree from Hartford Seminary in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1955. He is a member of Alpha Phi Alpha fraternity. Young was appointed to serve as pastor of a church in Marion, Alabama. It was there in Marion that he met Jean Childs, who later became his wife. Young became interested in Mahatma Gandhi's concept of nonviolent resistance as a tactic for social change. He encouraged African Americans to register to vote in Alabama, and sometimes faced death threats while doing so. It was at this time that he became a friend and ally of Martin Luther King Jr. In 1955 he accepted a pastorate at Bethany Congregational Church in Thomasville, Georgia. In 1957, Young and Jean moved to New York City when he accepted a job with the Youth Division of the National Council of Churches. While in New York City, Young regularly appeared on Look Up and Live, a weekly Sunday morning television program on CBS, produced by the National Council of Churches in an effort to reach out to secular youth. Young served as a pastor of the Evergreen Congregational Church in Beachton, Georgia, from 1957 to 1959. In 1960, he joined the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. No longer satisfied with his work in New York City, Young moved to Atlanta, Georgia, in 1961 upon the invitation of Bernard Lafayette and worked to register black voters. Young played a key role in the 1963 events in Birmingham, Alabama, serving as a mediator between the white and black communities as they negotiated against a background of protests. In 1964, Young was named executive director of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. As a colleague and friend of Martin Luther King Jr., he was a strategist and negotiator during the Civil Rights Campaigns in Birmingham (1963), St. Augustine (1964), Selma (1965), and Atlanta (1966). He was jailed for his participation in civil rights demonstrations, both in Selma, Alabama, and in St. Augustine, Florida. The movement gained congressional passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965. Young was with King in Memphis, Tennessee, when King was assassinated in 1968. In 1970, Young ran as a Democrat for the 5th District seat in the US House of Representatives, from Georgia, but was unsuccessful. After his defeat, Rev. Fred C. Bennette Jr. introduced him to Murray M. Silver, an Atlanta attorney, who served as his campaign finance chairman. Young ran again in 1972 and won. He later was re-elected in 1974 and in 1976. During his four-plus years in Congress, he was a member of the Congressional Black Caucus, and was involved in several debates regarding foreign relations, including the decision to stop supporting the Portuguese attempts to hold on to their colonies in southern Africa. Young also sat on the powerful Rules Committee and the Banking and Urban Development Committee. Young opposed the Vietnam War, helped enact legislation that established the U.S. Institute for Peace, established the Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area and negotiated federal funds for MARTA and the Atlanta Highways. In 1977, President Jimmy Carter appointed Young to serve as the United States Ambassador to the United Nations. Young was the first African American to hold the position. Atlanta city councilman Wyche Fowler won the special election to fill Young's seat in Congress. Although the US and the UN enacted an arms embargo against South Africa, as President Carter's UN ambassador, Young vetoed economic sanctions. In 1981, after being urged by a number of people, including Coretta Scott (truncated)

Please congratulate our HOSA State Leadership Conference Team on their successful State Leadership Conference. Twenty-seven "Dream Factory" students were among the 4,209 other HOSA Members who attended the conference from March 1st through 4th at the Atlanta Marriott Marquis. In addition to the conference, our HOSA students visited the Georgia Museum of Aviation, attended a personal guided tour of the State Capital hosted by Senator Watson, Representative Chas Cannon and their staff, and rode MARTA through Atlanta.

Some bad ideas never die. MARTA released details last fall on a plan to extend its streetcar 2.5 miles to Atlanta‚Äôs Beltline.

The first line of the Atlanta Streetcar system was implemented in 2015 and has been a terribly inefficient public transit program since its implementation. 

The numbers speak for themselves:

- The cost of the first 2.7 miles exceeded estimates at $99 million, or $36.7 million a mile, in 2015. In 2023, estimated costs ballooned to between $88 million to $107.5 million a mile for the proposed expansion with total project costs ranging from $176 million to $230 million.
- Even when it was free, ridership was significantly below capacity, and now that the line costs $1 a ride, ridership has sunk to an average of 400 riders a day in 2022. 
- The system has an average traveling speed of 5 mph. Considering the average human walking speed is 2.5 to 4 mph, it‚Äôs not unfair to say Atlanta‚Äôs streetcars are one of the slowest forms of public transportation available.

Rather than an expensive project that will serve a limited area and has limited demand by people living there, we should be looking at solutions that are a better fit for commuters of necessity, will actually reduce car usage within the city and be cost effective for taxpayers.

Read more: https://www.georgiapolicy.org/news/atlanta-streetcar-grand-plans-and-failed-ambitions/

post_body_text: Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens says extending the Atlanta Streetcar east and west from its current route is one of his priorities as the city negotiates with MARTA about a revised transit expansion project list.

Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens says extending the Atlanta Streetcar east and west from its current route is one of his priorities as the city negotiates with MARTA about a revised transit expansion project list. https://t.co/u8YZv3mktn
MARTA is tentatively moving ahead with plans for an Atlanta Streetcar extension even as it scrambles to restart the troubled rail line.

ICYMI: MARTA suspended streetcar rail service in November because of safety concerns and to repair the streetcar‚Äôs wheels. Since then, MARTA has operated specially marked shuttle vans along the route.

Mr. Coy Dumas, Jr. is a dedicated servant of our community and I am proud to have honored his unprecedented 50 years of service to City of Atlanta and Fulton County residents. Additionaly, Mr. Dumas was honored by the MARTA Board of Directors with a MARTA bus wrapped with his photo. 

MARTA 

#Heartwork #FulcoD4 #FultonCounty #Atlanta #CommissionerNatalieHall #OneFulton

Congratulations to Mr. Coy Dumas, Jr., The Department of Real Estate Asset Management, and The Public Works Department on being recognized for your service to City of Atlanta and Fulton County residents. 

The Department of Real Estate and Asset Management (DREAM) has two employees, Benjamin Wright, a Central Fulton Building Maintenance Supervisor, and Patrick Ent, a Greater Fulton Building Maintenance Supervisor, along with Department Director Joe Davis, that worked through the entirety of both County holiday periods, responding to facility issues at 16 buildings. Their response included securing the affected plumbing and fire sprinkler systems, facilitating necessary repairs in conjunction with contractors, and providing daily access to restoration contractors. 

The Public Works Department has a total of 14 employees that worked through the holiday weekend and repaired two major water main leaks, one on Marietta Street in Alpharetta and the other on Haynes Bridge Road in Johns Creek, as well as answered over 130 calls from residents with frozen pipes. Staff assisted homeowners with turning off water to their homes to minimize damage to their properties. 

Mr. Coy Dumas, Jr. is a native of the Adamsville community of Atlanta, Georgia and in 1972, joined what was then called Atlanta Transit as a bus operator. As a native of the Westside, he covered the West Atlanta routes and currently operates Route 853 out of the West Lake Station on the Blue Line. MARTA officials estimates that Mr. Dumas has carried approximately 2.8 million passengers on his bus since beginning his career in transit 50 years ago.

Mr. Dumas boasts a spotless driving record over his career and has never had a traffic accident. He is MARTA‚Äôs most veteran bus driver and wears operator badge #1. He's also been a mentor to countless bus operators over the past five decades, leads the Mentorship Program at the Perry Bus Facility, and he's made no plans to retire. 

 In commemoration of his unprecedented 50 years of dedicated service, Mr. Dumas was honored by the MARTA Board of Directors with a MARTA bus wrapped with his photo.

GoogleAudioText: Going to your New Year's Eve events is smarter on Marta, Marta tells 11 alive, more trains will run on New Year's Eve for the Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl in the Peach drop. Here's what you need to know. Beginning at noon, trains will run every 7 1/2 minutes on the red and gold lines between the Lindbergh station and the airport, as well as the blue and green line from the Ashby station to King Memorial. Then, at around 5:00, o'clock service is going to speed up to every 6 minutes for a full list of those routes and times had 211 alive.com. And it's not just. Partygoers counting down to the countdown, Atlanta police is also getting ready today. They are expected to give an update on the preparations the department is making for New Year's Eve events. They plan to lay out some of their safety measures. Today. 11 Alive will have a crew there and we'll bring you those details on air and online. And don't forget, Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens is hosting this year's Peach drop. Jermaine Dupree. He's headlining with special guest at Brat, Jagged Edge and Youngbloods. All the fun kicks off at 6:00 PM at underground Atlanta. With the Peach dropping at midnight.

post_body_text: NEW: MARTA is making another attempt at redeveloping property at its Arts Center station in Midtown Atlanta into a live-work-play hub after previous efforts failed to get off the ground.

NEW: MARTA is making another attempt at redeveloping property at its Arts Center station in Midtown Atlanta into a live-work-play hub after previous efforts failed to get off the ground. https://t.co/IQsabhnS8e

Get your walking shoes ready and your rainbow flags out! The Fulton Dems will be marching alongside our Senators, Stacey Abrams and the rest of our statewide slate in the Atlanta Pride Parade on Sunday, October 9! We'll meet up at the Civic Center MARTA Station between 9:30am and 11:00am for a noon step-off. See you there! #atlantapride22

PRIDE PARADE INFORMATION. PLEASE READ ALL THE INSTRUCTIONS CAREFULLY. The 2022 Atlanta Pride Parade is almost here and there's still time to be part of this fun event. Join the Cherokee County Democrats, Indivisible GA11, Antonio Daza, Micheal Garza, Sean Jackson, Katie McCree, Willie Mae Oyogoa, Patricia Stephenson, Kayla Hollifield, Bob Christian, and fellow democrats from Bartow and Pickens County as we walk in the Pride Parade on Sunday, October 9. Please read the following instructions carefully: Parade Information: The best way to get to the parade is to take Marta to the Civic Center exit. Check in is between 9:30 - 11:00 AM. Per the Pride Parade Committee, anyone arriving later than 11:00 AM may find themselves being placed at the back of the parade and not with our group. Be sure to give yourself plenty of time to get there by 11:00 AM. Add extra time into your travel plans for any unexpected delays. We are part of the Political Groups and we're assigned to block 3. When you get off Marta at the Civic Center head to our set-up spot on Bridge-Peachtree St and Baker St. Cherokee County Democrats placement order is 9 and Indivisible GA11 is 10. There are multiple staging areas. You need to find us at the described location. There will be many Atlanta PRIDE Parade volunteers on-hand if you run into any difficulties finding us. You're encouraged to wear Cherokee County Democrats t-shirts, Indivisible t-shirts or candidate t-shirts. Feel free to embellish them with colorful items reflecting Pride. You can carry signs. Make your own sign or bring a candidate sign. You can also pass out candy, however do not throw any items into the crowd. The day of the parade we will post Rain Rose's phone number should you have any questions. HAVE FUN

On November 27, 1994, El-Amin allegedly shot a man in the face with a handgun at the Oakland Street train station. The man died of his wounds. A man who'd been wanted in Atlanta for murder for nearly 28 years was finally caught this week during a routine traffic stop, according to the FBI.

The agency said in a release that Muhammed Bilal El-Amin was captured by the Oconee County Sheriff's Office, near Athens, in the course of the traffic stop.

It was not clear how deputies tied El-Amin to the 1994 crime during the traffic stop.

He'd had a FBI reward out for his arrest since the early 2000s, after allegedly shooting a man in the face with a handgun at the Oakland City MARTA station in Atlanta in November 1994.

MARTA will hold a job fair for bus operators and journeyman bus technicians on Thursday, July 7, from 3 p.m. until 7 p.m. at MARTA headquarters, located across from the Lindbergh Center rail station on Piedmont Road in Atlanta. MARTA is offering a $3,000 sign on bonus and will train all Permit and Class C (regular) license holders for their Commercial Driver‚Äôs License (CDL). See CDL requirements here.

See details on the job fair and requirements below:

WHAT:  Bus Operator and Journeyman Bus Technician Job FairPay starting at $17.74/hr. for operators and $23.91/hr. for technicians
MARTA will train all Permit and Class C (regular) license holders for their CDL                             
$3,000 sign-on bonus 
COVID-19 vaccination required for employment

WHEN: Thursday, July 7, 2022: 3 p.m. ‚Äì 7 p.m.
WHERE:  MARTA Headquarters, 2424 Piedmont Rd. NE, Atlanta, Ga. 30324                  

BUS OPERATOR REQUIREMENTS: Seeking full-time and part-time operators
Must be 21 years of age or older                                             
Must have high school diploma or equivalent
Must have current Class C (regular) license   
Must pass physical exam and ability test, and drug/alcohol screening
 
JOURNEYMAN BUS TECHINICIAN REQUIREMENTS:
Must be 18 years of age or older
Must have high school diploma or equivalent
Must have current Class C (regular) license                                          
Must have completed auto, transit bus, diesel, or maintenance programs, or have three or more years of comparable work experience
 
Applicants are encouraged to ride MARTA to the event. The job fair will be held at MARTA headquarters, which is located across the street from Lindbergh Center Station. Free parking is also available in the nearby MARTA parking deck.
 
Check for upcoming career fairs and employment opportunities by visiting MARTA (itsmarta.com) or calling 404-848-5544.
